For if it be an orator's part to be able to speak on any subject whatever that is laid before him in general terms, he will have to discuss the size of the sun and the contour of the earth ; and after under- taking this duty he will not be able to refuse to handle mathematics or the cult of the Muses. In a word, for the man who claims the right to speak‚ not only on problems identified with speeific times and persons (that is, on all judicial issues), but also on propositions of an abstract character, there can be no sort of debate which he can decline.
